entry.title: [setup] Stop CloseHandle crash in child proc
entry.content:
When updating an enterprise install of Chrome (i.e., one that originates

from the MSI installer), setup.exe spins off a child process to update

the DisplayVersion value in the registry after MSIExec finishes with it.

The child is given the handle to an event that it will signal when it's

ready to do its work. For some clients, this handle is invalid. Our

ScopedHandle helper will helpfully crash the process in this case, which

is not what we want. I have tried and tried to force the handle value

given to the child to be invalid, yet I fail every time. It is my belief

that some other software on client machines is interfering with the

event handle. So, in this CL, we now handle a failure to signal the

event by releasing the ScopedHandle so that we also don't try to close

the event. This should stop the crashes. We also temporarily send a

non-fatal dump if signaling the event fails for any reason other than

ERROR_INVALID_HANDLE.

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Redistribute shortcut boosting
entry.content:
ML scoring redistribute the traditional scores of the ML-scored

suggestions. The goal was to keep the balance between ML-scored and

non-ML-scored suggestions and avoid search regressions.



This CL makes ML scoring also redistribute the `shortcut_boosted` field

to the highest ML scored suggestions. The goal is the same; since this

field also affects ranking, we want to keep the same before/after

balance.



E.g., if we had this traditional ranking:

- shortcut 1, 1416 boosted defaultable

- shortcut 2, 1415 boosted defaultable

- search 1, 1300 defaultable

- search 2, 800

- url 3, 1414 defaultable

- url 4, 1200

- url 5, 600



Then before this CL, ML might give:

- url 3, 1414 defaultable

- search 1, 1300 defaultable

- shortcut 1, 1200 boosted defaultable

- search 2, 800

- shortcut 2, 600 boosted defaultable

- url 4, 1400

- url 5, 1416



That's bad because a) we broke search grouping, and b) search ranking

wasn't held constant. Also, in other examples, c) we might be changing

the default suggestion from a shortcut to a search.



With this CL, ML would instead give:

- url 3, 1414 boosted defaultable

- url 5, 1416 boosted

- search 1, 1300 defaultable

- search 2, 800

- url 4, 1400

- shortcut 1, 1200 defaultable

- shortcut 2, 600 defaultable



This keeps the same search v non-search rankings in this example.



This isn't a complete solution. There's still cases (both with and

without shortcut boosting) where ML will change the default suggestion

from non-search to search or vice versa or increase the # of URLs

grouped above searches. See the test for examples. That's an issue

regardless of shortcut boosting. We'll do a more robust fix as a

followup.

entry.title: snap-groups: Check `CanEnterOverview()` before SplitViewOverviewSession
entry.content:
This fixes a bug where new windows would get auto-snapped because

SplitViewOverviewSession was still alive, even though Overview wasn't,

which is why it wasn't visually noticed until now.



The cause of the bug is:

1. When the second window gets auto-snapped from

SplitViewOverviewSession, it calls `EndOverview()`.

2. `SnapGroupController::OnOverviewModeEnded()` would call `RestoreSnapStates()` to snap the windows.

3. `OnWindowSnapped()` will try to start SplitViewOverviewSession again.



During this time, we should enforce

`SnapGroupController::can_enter_overview_`, which we

can do by checking `OverviewController::Get()->CanEnterOverview()`.

entry.title: Add 2 compilators for chromeos-amd64-generic-rel-gtest(-and-tast) builders
entry.content:
The initial plan was to share compilator. But with the current design,

sharing the compilators isn't possible unless the orchestrators have

the same properties, which would mean they would need to mirror the

same builders. For sharing compilators, we would need to switch it

so that the compilators get all of the builder-specific properties

from the orchestrator, so for example the builder config would need

to be sent by the orchestrator.



We changed the design to use 2 compilators for

chromeos-amd64-generic-rel-gtest and

chromeos-amd64-generic-rel-gtest-and-tast builders. The 2

compilators share the same named cache.

entry.title: view-transition: Implement PseudoAware tree traversals
entry.content:
Pseudo elements like those in the ::view-transition subtree aren't

actually part of the standard DOM tree, they inaccessible via methods

like firstChild and nextSibling.



This revealed a bug from a test written for https://crbug.com/1495157.

The document.getAnimations() method requires that the returned

Animations be sorted by compositing order which requires sorting based

on document order. However, the document order comparison uses next and

previous siblings which breaks down on pseudos. This likely wasn't a

problem in the past as view-transition pseudos are (I think) the first

that can be animated but it means the comparator doesn't satisfy the

required strict-weak-ordering condition.



This can cause crashes in the std::sort method. I was only able to

observe this on Android, likely due to differences in the std::sort

implementation.



There are existing "PseudoAware" methods on Node that don't yet

implement traversal for ::view-transition and descendants so this CL

fills those out and replaces sibling usage in the document order

comparison with the PseudoAware versions.

entry.title: exo: respect DRM_FORMAT_MOD_LINEAR
entry.content:
sommelier uses DRM_IOCTL_VIRTGPU_RESOURCE_INFO_CROS and falls back to

DRM_FORMAT_MOD_INVALID. The ioctl returns the info queried from

virgl_renderer_export_query which calls gbm_bo_get_modifier in the host.



arc++/arcvm uses GRALLOC_DRM_GET_BUFFER_INFO and falls back to

DRM_FORMAT_MOD_LINEAR. On arcvm, the query uses

DRM_IOCTL_VIRTGPU_RESOURCE_INFO_CROS. On arc++, the query calls

drv_bo_get_format_modifier.



Other than the arc++/arcvm fallback, which should never happen,

DRM_FORMAT_MOD_LINEAR means linear. We don't need the workaround

anymore.



The workaround treats DRM_FORMAT_MOD_LINEAR as DRM_FORMAT_MOD_INVALID.

VulkanImplementationGbm::CreateImageFromGpuMemoryHandle picks

VK_IMAGE_TILING_OPTIMAL when the modifier is invalid. That breaks

imports of linear buffers.

entry.title: Don't link the component updater into libsoda
entry.content:
The update client is defined as a static library rather than a

component. For various reasons, it would be difficult to refactor the

library to be a component. This has lead to a situation in which

updater client symbols are duplicated across different dynamic

libraries (e.g. libsoda & libchrome).



Typically, having duplicate symbols from different dynamic libraries

is not an issue, however duplicate Objective-C classes will cause a

log warning to be fired. We recently added a background downloader on

Mac which has Obj-C classes. The warning message fires very frequently

in component builds of Chrome, which is quite annoying.



To fix this, we would like to have libsoda not include this symbol. To

do so, we have separated the path definitions into a separate static

library for SODA to depend on.

entry.title: Advance time until all reports have been consumed in interop runner
entry.content:
Rather than trying to track the maximum report time directly, which is

prone to imprecision: prior to this change, time wouldn't be advanced

properly with respect to fake reports, null reports, report retries, or

offline report-time adjustments, though none of those behaviors is

capable of occurring during interop testing at this point. This change

future-proofs the interop runner to account for them while

simultaneously decoupling behavior of the interop runner from that of

the real system.



We use a loop rather than getting the maximum report time only once

because the act of trying to send a report can cause its report time to

change due to transmission failure.

entry.title: Revert "Update obsolete_system"
entry.content:
This reverts the effective parts of commit

c58a7364817b346bf6fb169ee69c94cbfadee41e.



That commit showed a complete misunderstanding of what

StartOutdatedBuildDetector does (sorry!). StartOutdatedBuildDetector

is a belt-and-suspenders backup that says that if a build is more than

8 weeks old, it surely is out of date. It doesn't actually drive the

normal update mechanism, and disabling it for end-of-the-line

Chromes is absolutely the right thing to do.



(This revert keeps the cleanup and reformatting parts of that commit.)
